\section*{stat\_\allowbreak{}optimal\_\allowbreak{}value\_\allowbreak{}honest\_\allowbreak{}adaptation}

\noindent\textit{Specialization:} binary\_\allowbreak{}optimal\_\allowbreak{}value\_\allowbreak{}sparse\_\allowbreak{}neartie\_\allowbreak{}adaptation\par

\paragraph{TL;DR.} Under iid sampling, known one-half randomization, bounded outcomes, Hölder outcome regressions, and a margin condition that permits a tie atom, a sparse randomized-sign experiment forces every union-honest connected interval for the optimal policy value to have expected length at least \(n^{-1/2}\vee n^{-\xi}\) at the exact-tie base law, where \(\xi=2s_1(\alpha+1)/(d+s_1\alpha+4s_1)\). The explicit split-sample learned-policy interval \(C_n^\dagger\) is uniformly honest and has length \(O(n^{-1/2}+n^{-\rho})\), where \(\rho=s_1(\alpha+1)/(2s_1+d)\). These scales coincide at root \(n\) when \(2s_1\alpha\ge d\); outside that subregime, attainment of the sparse lower scale by the distinct hypothetical multiscale interval \(C_n^{\mathrm{ms}}\) remains open.

\section{Project justification}

\paragraph{Gap.} Existing inference for exceptional optimal-treatment laws does not provide this two-stratum expected-length adaptation diagram for a connected interval that is honest simultaneously over exact ties and Hölder near ties with an allowed tie atom. The unresolved issue is sharply localized: when \(2s_1\alpha<d\), the proved lower exponent \(\min\{1/2,\xi\}\) and achievable exponent \(\min\{1/2,\rho\}\) differ.

\paragraph{Niche.} The note studies honest adaptation for the causal optimal-policy value, taking its randomized-trial identifying functional as given. Its distinctive ingredients are an explicit dominated sparse causal mixture for the lower bound and a single data-driven split-sample learned-policy interval for the upper bound.

\paragraph{Fill.} The lower calculation holds for every admissible pair; the inequality \(3s_1\alpha<d\) is needed only for the corollary that the sparse scale is strictly slower than root \(n\). Combining that calculation with a parametric tie submodel gives the unified lower scale \(n^{-1/2}\vee n^{-\xi}\) on both strata. The proved split-sample interval \(C_n^\dagger\) supplies the honest upper scale \(n^{-1/2}+n^{-\rho}\); the symbol \(C_n^{\mathrm{ms}}\) is reserved for the unresolved multiscale route.

\section{Related work}

Luedtke--van der Laan and subsequent work analyze inference at exceptional laws, while policy-learning results supply regret control under smoothness and margin conditions. Cai--Low-style testing arguments explain how indistinguishable alternatives constrain expected interval length, and Armstrong--Kolesar emphasize the cost of honest bias control under predeclared restrictions. Ponomarev--Semenova and Liu--Liu--Sasaki--Wan address related non-uniqueness-robust or representative-policy inference problems. None of those results supplies the present explicit sparse randomized-sign causal product experiment together with this exact-tie/near-tie union bracket. The current result is a proved lower/upper bracket, not a claim of a globally matched frontier.

